SIMPLE: ring
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ring
<hw>Ring</hw> <pr>(r⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Rang</conjf> <pr>(r⟦acr⟧ng)</pr> or
<conjf>Rung</conjf> <pr>(r⟦ucr⟧ng)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Rung</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ringing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>hringan</ets>; akin to
Icel. <ets>hringja</ets>, Sw. <ets>ringa</ets>, Dan. <ets>ringe</ets>,
OD. <ets>ringhen</ets>, <ets>ringkelen</ets>. ⟦root⟧19.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to sound, especially by striking, as a
metallic body; <as>as, to <ex>ring</ex> a bell</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make (a sound), as by ringing a bell; to
sound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The shard-borne beetle, with his drowsy hums,⟦br⟧
Hath <qex>rung</qex> night's yawning peal.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To repeat often, loudly, or earnestly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To ring a peal</b></col>, <cd>to ring a set of changes on
a chime of bells.</cd> -- <col><b>To ring the changes upon</b></col>.
<cd>See under <er>Change</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To ring
in</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To ring out</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to
usher, attend on, or celebrate, by the ringing of bells; <as>as, <ex>to
ring out</ex> the old year and <ex>ring in</ex> the new</as>.</cd>
<au>Tennyson</au>. -- <col><b>To ring the bells backward</b></col>,
<cd>to sound the chimes, reversing the common order; -- formerly done as
a signal of alarm or danger.</cd> <au>Sir W. Scott.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ring</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ring
<hw>Ring</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To sound, as a bell or
other sonorous body, particularly a metallic one.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now <qex>ringen</qex> trompes loud and clarion.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why <qex>ring</qex> not out the bells?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To practice making music with bells.</def>
<rj><au>Holder.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To sound loud; to resound; to be filled with a
ringing or reverberating sound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With sweeter notes each rising temple <qex>rung</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The hall with harp and carol <qex>rang</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My ears still <qex>ring</qex> with noise.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To continue to sound or vibrate; to
resound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The assertion is still <qex>ringing</qex> in our ears.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To be filled with report or talk; <as>as, the whole
town <ex>rings</ex> with his fame</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ring</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Ring
<hw>Ring</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A sound; especially, the
sound of vibrating metals; <as>as, the <ex>ring</ex> of a
bell</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any loud sound; the sound of numerous voices; a
sound continued, repeated, or reverberated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>ring</qex> of acclamations fresh in his ears.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A chime, or set of bells harmonically
tuned.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As great and tunable a <qex>ring</qex> of bells as any in the
world.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ring</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Ring
<hw>Ring</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>hring</ets>,
<ets>hrinc</ets>; akin to Fries. <ets>hring</ets>, D. & G.
<ets>ring</ets>, OHG. <ets>ring</ets>, <ets>hring</ets>, Icel.
<ets>hringr</ets>, DAn. & SW. <ets>ring</ets>; cf. Russ.
<ets>krug'</ets>. Cf. <er>Harangue</er>, <er>Rank</er> a
row,<er>Rink</er>.]</ety> <def>A circle, or a circular line, or anything
in the form of a circular line or hoop.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically, a circular ornament of gold or other
precious material worn on the finger, or attached to the ear, the nose,
or some other part of the person; <as>as, a wedding
<ex>ring</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Upon his thumb he had of gold a <qex>ring</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The dearest <qex>ring</qex> in Venice will I give you.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A circular area in which races are or run or other
sports are performed; an arena.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Place me, O, place me in the dusty <qex>ring</qex>,⟦br⟧
Where youthful charioteers contend for glory.</q> <rj><qau>E.
Smith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An inclosed space in which pugilists fight; hence,
figuratively, prize fighting.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The road was an institution,
the <xex>ring</xex> was an institution.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A circular group of persons.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And hears the Muses in a <qex>ring</qex>⟦br⟧
Aye round about Jove's alter sing.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The plane figure
included between the circumferences of two concentric circles.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>The solid generated by the revolution of a circle, or
other figure, about an exterior straight line (as an axis) lying in the
same plane as the circle or other figure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Astron. & Navigation)</fld> <def>An instrument,
formerly used for taking the sun's altitude, consisting of a brass ring
suspended by a swivel, with a hole at one side through which a solar ray
entering indicated the altitude on the graduated inner surface
opposite.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An elastic band partly or wholly
encircling the spore cases of ferns. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of
<er>Sporangium</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>A clique; an exclusive combination of persons for a
selfish purpose, as to control the market, distribute offices, obtain
contracts, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ruling <qex>ring</qex> at Constantinople.</q> <rj><qau>E. A.
Freeman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ring armor</b></col>, <cd>armor composed of rings of
metal. See <cref>Ring mail</cref>, below, and <cref>Chain mail</cref>,
under <er>Chain</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Ring blackbird</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the ring ousel.</cd> -- <col><b>Ring
canal</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the circular water tube which
surrounds the esophagus of echinoderms.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Ring
dotterel</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Ringed
dotterel</b></col></mcol>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Dotterel</er>,
and <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Pressiroster</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Ring
dropper</b></col>, <cd>a sharper who pretends to have found a ring
(dropped by himself), and tries to induce another to buy it as valuable,
it being worthless.</cd> -- <col><b>Ring fence</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Fence</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Ring finger</b></col>, <cd>the third
finger of the left hand, or the next the little finger, on which the
ring is placed in marriage.</cd> -- <col><b>Ring formula</b></col>
<fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a graphic formula in the shape of a closed ring,
as in the case of benzene, pyridine, etc. See <xex>Illust.</xex> under
<er>Benzene</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Ring mail</b></col>, <cd>a kind of
mail made of small steel rings sewed upon a garment of leather or of
cloth.</cd> -- <col><b>Ring micrometer</b></col>. <fld>(Astron.)</fld>
<cd>See <cref>Circular micrometer</cref>, under
<er>Micrometer</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Saturn's rings</b></col>. <cd>See
<er>Saturn</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Ring ousel</b></col>.
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Ousel</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Ring
parrot</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of several species of
Old World parrakeets having a red ring around the neck, especially
<spn>Palaeornis torquatus</spn>, common in India, and <spn>Palaeornis
Alexandri</spn> of <er>Java</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Ring plover</b></col>.
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The ringed dotterel</cd>.
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Any one of several small American plovers having a dark
ring around the neck, as the semipalmated plover (<spn>Aegialitis
semipalmata</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>Ring snake</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a small harmless American snake (<spn>Diadophis
punctatus</spn>) having a white ring around the neck. The back is
ash-colored, or sage green, the belly of an orange red.</cd> --
<col><b>Ring stopper</b></col>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>See under
<er>Stopper</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Ring thrush</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the ring ousel.</cd> -- <col><b>The prize
ring</b></col>, <cd>the ring in which prize fighters contend; prize
fighters, collectively.</cd> -- <col><b>The ring</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>The body of sporting men who bet on horse races</cd>.
<mark>[Eng.]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The prize ring.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ring</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Ring
<hw>Ring</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Ringed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ringing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To surround with a
ring, or as with a ring; to encircle.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Ring</xex> these
fingers.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Hort.)</fld> <def>To make a ring around by cutting
away the bark; to girdle; <as>as, to <ex>ring</ex> branches or
roots</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To fit with a ring or with rings, as the fingers, or
a swine's snout.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ring</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Ring
<hw>Ring</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <fld>(Falconry)</fld> <def>To rise in
the air spirally.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ring armature</ent>⟦br⟧
